04893nam a22007455i 9789400604247DE-B159720240306015011.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023ne     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1396937837  a97894006042477 a10.1515/97894006042472doi  a(DE-B1597)635242  a(OCoLC)1369644702  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aHIS0170002bisacsh04a349.54931 aRupesinghe, Nadeera, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLawmaking in Dutch Sri Lanka :bNavigating Pluralities in a Colonial Society /cNadeera Rupesinghe. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (316 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColonial and Global History through Dutch Sources ;v600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Maps, Figures and Tables -- tAcknowledgements -- tNotes on Usage -- tGlossary -- tMaps -- tINTRODUCTION Conjecture and Deliberation -- tCHAPTER 1 Building the Landraad -- tCHAPTER 2 Divided Authority -- tCHAPTER 3 Facing the Law -- tCHAPTER 4 Marshalling Unseen Forces -- tCHAPTER 5 Defining Land Rights -- tCHAPTER 6 On Inheriting Land -- tCONCLUSION Revisiting Colonial Legal Practice -- tAPPENDIX I European Members at the Galle Landraad 1759–96 -- tAPPENDIX II Rulers of Kandy and Dutch Governors -- tAPPENDIX III List of Accommodessan Grants -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNavigating Pluralities marks a break in understanding the history of Roman-Dutch law in Sri Lanka. Methodologically, it challenges socio-legal studies that concentrate on major jurisdictional conflicts alone, emphasizing the lived experience of everyday practices of judicial forums. It uncovers the navigation of plural practices in the Landraad, a judicial forum set up by the Dutch East India Company in seventeenth-century Sri Lanka. A choice of laws came into play in that forum, that choice being significant at varying degrees for different areas of the law such as evidence, inheritance, land, and marriage law. While there was inevitable conflict, the local normative order was as much a social fact for the early colonial rulers as Roman-Dutch law. This is contrary to the received wisdom of the ages that Roman-Dutch law was imposed on the Sinhalese of the maritime provinces under Dutch control. When translated into everyday lives, such adoption of plural practices could rebound on coloniser and colonised in unexpected ways, revealing the complexities of colonial law in practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aLaw. 4aSouth Asia. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh  aDutch East India Company, VOC, Roman-Dutch Law, Colonial Law, History of Sri Lanka, Legal Pluralism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102374808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG0 cprintz978908728375940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978940060424740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789400604247423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789400604247/original  a978-3-11-102374-8  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131913-1  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  aEBA_CL